The this keyword in JavaScript is a special reference that points to the object that is currently executing the code.
Its value changes depending on how and where the function is called â€” not where itâ€™s written.

1ï¸âƒ£ In an object method
this refers to the object before the dot.
const person = {
  name: "Mahi",
  greet: function () {
    console.log(this.name); // 'this' refers to person object
  }
};

person.greet(); // Mahi
2ï¸âƒ£ Alone (in global scope)
In non-strict mode, this refers to the global object (window in browsers).

In strict mode, this is undefined.
console.log(this); // window (browser)
"use strict";
console.log(this); // undefined
3ï¸âƒ£ In a function
Non-strict mode â†’ this is the global object.

Strict mode â†’ this is undefined.

function show() {
  console.log(this);
}
show(); // window (non-strict) or undefined (strict)
4ï¸âƒ£ In a constructor function or class
When used inside a constructor or class, this refers to the newly created object.

function Car(brand) {
  this.brand = brand;
}
const car1 = new Car("BMW"); 
console.log(car1.brand); // BMW
5ï¸âƒ£ In an event listener
this refers to the HTML element that triggered the event.

document.querySelector("button").addEventListener("click", function() {
  console.log(this); // the button element
});
6ï¸âƒ£ Arrow functions and this
Arrow functions do not have their own this.
They inherit this from the surrounding scope.

const obj = {
  name: "Mahi",
  greet: () => {
    console.log(this.name); // undefined (inherits from global scope)
  }
};
obj.greet();
ðŸ’¡ In short:
this = Who is calling me right now?

In an object method â†’ the object.

In a class/constructor â†’ the new object being created.

Alone or in a function â†’ global object (or undefined in strict mode).

Arrow function â†’ parent's this.

